 \n| {{ya}}\n| \n| \n| {{ya}}\n| \n| \n|\n| \n|\n|\n|-\n! [[Michael Shamus Wiles]]\n| \n|\n| \n| {{ya}}\n| \n| \n| {{ya}}\n| \n| \n|\n| \n|\n|\n|-\n! [[Megan Fox]]\n|\n|\n| \n| \n| {{ya}}\n| \n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| \n|\n| \n|\n|\n|-\n! [[Brian Stepanek]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n|\n|\n| {{ya}}\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! [[Shia LaBeouf]]\n|\n| \n| \n| \n|\n|\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| \n|\n|\n|\n|- \n! [[Josh Duhamel]]\n|\n| \n| \n| \n|\n|\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| \n|\n|\n| {{ya}}\n|- \n! [[John Turturro]]\n|\n| \n| \n| \n|\n|\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| \n|\n|\n| {{ya}}\n|-\n! [[Kevin Dunn]]\n|\n| \n| \n| \n|\n|\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| \n|\n|\n| \n|-\n! [[Hugo Weaving]]\n|\n| \n| \n| \n|\n|\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| \n| \n|\n|\n|-\n! [[Peter Cullen]]\n|\n| \n| \n| \n|\n|\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| \n| {{ya}}\n|\n| {{ya}}\n|-\n! [[Charlie Adler]]\n|\n| \n| \n| \n|\n|\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| \n|\n| \n|\n|-\n! [[Frank Welker]]\n|\n| \n| \n| \n|\n|\n| \n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| \n| {{ya}}\n|\n| {{ya}}\n|-\n! [[Reno Wilson]]\n|\n| \n| \n| \n|\n|\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| \n| {{ya}}\n|\n| {{ya}}\n|-\n! [[Robert Foxworth]]\n|\n| \n| \n| \n|\n|\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| \n| {{ya}}\n|\n|\n|-\n! [[John DiMaggio]]\n|\n| \n| \n| \n|\n|\n| \n| \n| {{ya}}\n| \n| {{ya}}\n|\n| {{ya}}\n|-\n! [[Mark Ryan (actor)|Mark Ryan]]\n|\n| \n| \n| \n|\n|\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| \n| \n| {{ya}}\n| \n| {{ya}}\n|-\n! [[Jess Harnell]]\n|\n| \n| \n| \n|\n|\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n| \n| \n| \n| {{ya}}\n|-\n! [[John Goodman]]\n|\n| \n| \n| \n|\n|\n| \n| \n| \n| \n| {{ya}}\n| \n| {{ya}}\n|-\n! [[Ken Watanabe]]\n|\n| \n| \n| \n|\n|\n| \n| \n| \n| \n| {{ya}}\n| \n| {{ya}}\n|-\n! [[Ken Jeong]]\n|\n| \n| \n| \n|\n|\n|\n|\n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n! [[Mark Wahlberg]]\n|\n| \n| \n| \n|\n|\n|\n|\n| \n| {{ya}}\n| {{ya}}\n|\n| {{ya}}\n|}\n\n== Critical reception ==\nDespite his box office success, Bay's work has been poorly received by film critics, and his name is often used [[pejorative]]ly in [[art film|art-house]] circles.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.avclub.com/article/heres-learned-analysis-why-michael-bay-movies-are--206582 |title=Here\u2019s a learned analysis of why Michael Bay movies are bad, but pretty |last=Selcke |first=Dan |date=July 7, 2014 |work=[[The A.V. Club]] |access-date=January 16, 2016}} \"No matter how many buildings, spacecrafts, and sentient robots Michael Bay explodes, the director can\u2019t seem to get any respect. His movies are panned by critics, and his bombastic filmmaking style is routinely mocked by respectable, erudite writers on the Internet.\"</ref> Bay has responded to his critics, saying \"I make movies for teenage boys. Oh, dear, what a crime.\"<ref>Curtis, Bryan (June 15, 2005). [http://www.slate.com/articles/news_and_politics/summer_movies/2005/06/the_bad_boy_of_summer.html \"The Bad Boy of Summer: Michael Bay vs. his Critics.\"] ''Slate.com''. Retrieved 2014-07-25.</ref> Besides being accused of making films that pander to a low demographic, critics and audiences have been critical of elements of Bay's filmmaking style such as the overuse of [[Dutch angle]]s, rapid cutting, and clich\u00e9 camerawork. Other elements include extreme patriotism, juvenile humor, excessive product placement, oversaturated orange and teal [[color grading]], reusing footage from his previous films, his refusal to make thought-provoking films, and his preference of action and spectacle over story and characters.<ref>{{Citation |last=WatchMojo.com |title=Top 10 Reasons Why Michael Bay Movies Are Hated |date=January 30, 2016 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8PIFpObY1ug |access-date=March 2, 2019}}</ref> Another point of contention with Bay's films is his portrayal and use of offensive racial stereotypes as comedic relief; a notable alleged example being the characters Skids and Mudflap in ''Transformers: Revenge of the Fallen''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.accessonline.com/articles/transformers-director-michael-bay-fends-off-racist-robot-criticism-72848 |title=\u2018Transformers\u2019 Director Michael Bay Fends Off Racist Robot Criticism {{!}} Access Online |date=June 24, 2009 |website=Access |language=en |access-date=March 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nBay has also been accused of heavily [[Objectification|objectifying]] women in his films, with critics describing Bay's manner of filming actresses as \"lascivious\" and \"pornographic\". He has also faced criticism for making sexist remarks and showing female characters in a stereotypical light. He came under fire for firing [[Megan Fox]] after she made comments about him mistreating her on the set of the ''Transformers'' films and compared him to [[Hitler]] and [[Napoleon]], and allegedly body-shaming [[Kate Beckinsale]] and being critical of her appearance during the making of ''[[Pearl Harbor (film)|Pearl Harbor]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.eonline.com/news/769220/michael-bay-s-chauvinist-reputation-remains-intact-and-no-one-seems-less-concerned-about-that-than-michael-bay |title=Michael Bay's Chauvinist Reputation Remains Intact and No One Seems Less Concerned About That Than Michael Bay |last=Finn |first=Natalie |date=June 1, 2016 |website=E! Online |language=en-US |access-date=March 2, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2014/06/how-to-tell-youre-a-woman-in-a-michael-bay-film.html |title=7 Ways to Tell You\u2019re a Woman in a Michael Bay Movie |last=Buchanan |first=Kyle |date=June 26, 2014 |website=www.vulture.com |access-date=March 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ [[Rotten Tomatoes]] ratings\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Film\n! scope=\"col\" | Rating\n|-\n| 1995 || ''[[Bad Boys (1995 film)|Bad Boys]]'' || 42%<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1062483-bad_boys/ |title=Rotten Tomatoes T-Meter Rating of ''Bad Boys'' |website=Rotten Tomatoes |access-date=February 20, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1996 || ''[[The Rock (film)|The Rock]]'' || 66%<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1072011-rock/ |title=Rotten Tomatoes T-Meter Rating of ''The Rock'' |website=Rotten Tomatoes |access-date=February 20, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1998 || ''[[Armageddon (1998 film)|Armageddon]]'' || 38%<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/armageddon/ |title=Rotten Tomatoes T-Meter Rating of ''Armageddon'' |website=Rotten Tomatoes |access-date=February 20, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2001 || ''[[Pearl Harbor (film)|Pearl Harbor]]'' || 24%<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1108389-pearl_harbor/ |title=Rotten Tomatoes T-Meter Rating of ''Pearl Harbor'' |website=Rotten Tomatoes |access-date=February 20, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2003 || ''[[Bad Boys II]]'' || 23%<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/bad_boys_ii/ |title=Rotten Tomatoes T-Meter Rating of ''Bad Boys II'' |website=Rotten Tomatoes |access-date=February 20, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2005 || ''[[The Island (2005 film)|The Island]]'' || 40%<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/island/ |title=Rotten Tomatoes T-Meter Rating of ''The Island'' |website=Rotten Tomatoes |access-date=February 20, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2007 || ''[[Transformers (film)|Transformers]]'' || 58%<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/transformers_the_movie/ |title=Rotten Tomatoes T-Meter Rating of ''Transformers'' |website=Rotten Tomatoes |access-date=February 20, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2009 || ''[[Transformers: Revenge of the Fallen]]'' || 20%<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/transformers_revenge_of_the_fallen/ |title=Rotten Tomatoes T-Meter Rating of ''Transformers: Revenge of the Fallen'' |website=Rotten Tomatoes |access-date=February 20, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2011 || ''[[Transformers: Dark of the Moon]]'' || 35%<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/transformers_dark_of_the_moon/ |title=Rotten Tomatoes T-Meter Rating of ''Transformers: Dark of the Moon'' |website=Rotten Tomatoes |access-date=February 20, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2013 || ''[[Pain & Gain]]'' || 50%<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/pain_and_gain/ |title=Rotten Tomatoes T-Meter Rating of ''Pain & Gain'' |website=Rotten Tomatoes |access-date=February 20, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2014 || ''[[Transformers: Age of Extinction]]'' || 18%<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/transformers_age_of_extinction/ |title=Transformers: Age of Extinction |website=Rotten Tomatoes |access-date=August 4, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2016 || ''[[13 Hours: The Secret Soldiers of Benghazi]]'' || 51%<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/13_hours_the_secret_soldiers_of_benghazi/ |title=13 Hours: The Secret Soldiers of Benghazi |website=Rotten Tomatoes |access-date=January 19, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2017 || ''[[Transformers: The Last Knight]]'' || 15%<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/transformers_the_last_knight_2017/ |title=Transformers: The Last Knight |website=Rotten Tomatoes |access-date=June 20, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2019 || ''[[6 Underground (film)|6 Underground]]'' || 37%<ref>{{cite web |title=6 Underground |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/6_underground |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=14 December 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |\n! scope=\"col\" | Average\n! scope=\"col\" | 37%\n|}\n\n==Accolades==\n{{Main|List of awards and nominations received by Michael Bay}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.michaelbay.com/}}\n* [http://www.theinstitute.tv/ The Institute]\n* {{IMDb name|0000881}}\n* {{AllRovi name|203853}}\n\n<!--spacing-->\n\n{{Michael Bay}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = [[List of awards and nominations received by Michael Bay|Awards for Michael Bay]]\n| list =\n{{DirectorsGuildofAmericaAwardCommercials}}\n{{MTV Movie Award for Best Action Sequence}}\n{{Saturn Award for Best Director}}\n}}\n{{Platinum Dunes}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bay, Michael}}\n[[Category:Michael Bay]]\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:American adoptees]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American film producers]]\n[[Category:American music video directors]]\n[[Category:Action film directors]]\n[[Category:Science fiction film directors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American people of Russian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Art Center College of Design alumni]]\n[[Category:Crossroads School alumni]]\n[[Category:Wesleyan University alumni]]\n[[Category:Television commercial directors]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Los Angeles]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American film director, film producer, camera operator and actor}}\n{{pp-semi-blp|small=yes}}\n{{Use American English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n|image         = Michael.bay.png\n|caption       = Bay in 2006\n|birth_name = Michael Benjamin Bay\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1965|2|17}}\n|birth_place   = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n|residence     = [[Miami, Florida]]<br /> [[Bel Air, California]]\n|nationality   = American\n|alma_mater    = [[Wesleyan University]]<br>[[Art Center College of Design]]\n|occupation    = Film director, producer, camera operator, actor\n|notable_works = {{Ubl|''[[Armageddon (1998 film)|Armageddon]]''|''[[Pearl Harbor (film)|Pearl Harbor]]''|[[Transformers (film series)|''Transformers'' film series]]}}\n|years_active  = 1986\u2013present\n|religion      = \n|relatives     = [[Leonard Nimoy]] (cousin-in-law)\n|website       = {{URL|http://www.michaelbay.com/}}\n}}\n'''Michael Benjamin Bay''' (born February 17, 1965)<ref>{{cite news|title=Monitor|newspaper=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=Feb 17, 2012|issue=1194|page=26}}</ref> is an American filmmaker known for directing and producing big-budget, [[high-concept]] action films characterized by [[fast cutting]], stylistic visuals and extensive use of [[special effect]]s, including frequent depictions of [[explosion]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slate.com/id/2120961|title=The Bad Boy of Summer|last=Curtis|first=Brian|work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]|publisher=[[The Slate Group]]|date=2005-06-15|accessdate=2010-07-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.screenjunkies.com/movienews/michael-bay-explosion-tournament|title=The Michael Bay Explosion Tournament|last=Schumacker|first=Patrick|last2=Sobel|first2=Ian|work=ScreenJunkies.com|date=2009-06-23|accessdate=2010-07-03|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090625182818/http://www.screenjunkies.com/movienews/michael-bay-explosion-tournament|archivedate=2009-06-25}}</ref> The films he has produced and directed, which include ''[[Armageddon (1998 film)|Armageddon]]'' (1998), ''[[Pearl Harbor (film)|Pearl Harbor]]'' (2001) and the [[Transformers (film series)|''Transformers'' film series]] (2007\u2013present), have grossed over {{US$|7.8 billion}} worldwide, making him one of the most [[List of highest-grossing directors|commercially successful directors in history]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/people/chart/?view=Director&id=michaelbay.htm|title=Michael Bay Movie Box Office Results|website=www.boxofficemojo.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/people/chart/?view=Producer&id=michaelbay.htm|title=Michael Bay Movie Box Office Results|website=www.boxofficemojo.com}}</ref>\n\nHe is co-founder of commercial production house The Institute, a.k.a. The Institute for the Development of Enhanced Perceptual Awareness.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theinstitute.tv/directors.php|title=The Institute|accessdate=2010-07-03|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101116123932/http://www.theinstitute.tv/directors.php|archivedate=2010-11-16}}</ref> He co-owns [[Platinum Dunes]], a production house which has remade [[horror film|horror]] movies including ''[[The Texas Chainsaw Massacre (2003 film)|The Texas Chainsaw Massacre]]'' (2003), ''[[The Amityville Horror (2005 film)|The Amityville Horror]]'' (2005), ''[[The Hitcher (2007 film)|The Hitcher]]'' (2007), ''[[Friday the 13th (2009 film)|Friday the 13th]]'' (2009) and ''[[A Nightmare on Elm Street (2010 film)|A Nightmare on Elm Street]]'' (2010).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117979807.html?categoryid=13&cs=1|title=New Line Sets Up New 'Nightmare'|last=Fleming|first=Michael|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Reed Elsevier]]|date=2008-01-29|accessdate=2010-07-03}}</ref>\n\nDespite his commercial success at the box office, Bay's work is generally held in low esteem by film critics. While ''[[The Rock (film)|The Rock]]'' (1996) and [[Transformers (film)|''Transformers'']] (2007) received moderately positive reviews, his other films, including the four ''Transformers'' sequels, have been received negatively by critics.\n\n==Early life==\nMichael Bay was born in Los Angeles. He was raised by his adoptive parents Harriet, a bookstore owner/[[child psychiatrist]], and Jim, a [[Certified Public Accountant]] (CPA).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/28/Michael-Bay.html|title=Michael Bay Biography (1965\u2013)|work=FilmReference.com|publisher=Advameg, Inc.|accessdate=2010-07-03}}</ref> Bay was raised [[Jewish]].<ref>[https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/biography/Michael_Bay.html Michael Bay] [[Jewish Virtual Library]] - retrieved July 23, 2013</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://forward.com/culture/film-tv/375181/why-the-transformers-movies-are-really-stories-of-jewish-resilience-and-ada/|title=The Secret Jewish History Of The Transformers|last=Abrams|first=Nathan|date=June 20, 2017|work=[[The Forward]]|accessdate=June 4, 2018|quote=As the adopted son of Jim and Harriet Bay, Michael was raised in a Jewish household.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://jewishbusinessnews.com/2014/04/23/michael-bay-transforms-his-transformers/|title=Michael Bay Transforms His Transformers|work=Jewish Business News|first=Joab|last=Nevo|date=April 23, 2014|accessdate=June 4, 2018}}</ref> His grandfather was from Russia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.orange.co.uk/article/news/linkin_park_rock_russian_transformers_premiere|title=Linkin Park Rocks Russian Transformers Premiere|work=Orange News|date=2011-06-24|accessdate=2011-07-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111001064804/http://web.orange.co.uk/article/news/linkin_park_rock_russian_transformers_premiere|archive-date=October 1, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> His cousin, [[Susan Bay]], is the widow of ''[[Star Trek]]'' actor [[Leonard Nimoy]] (whom he eventually cast as the voice actor for Sentinel Prime in ''[[Transformers: Dark of the Moon]]'').<ref>{{cite web|url=http://moviesblog.mtv.com/2009/04/21/michael-bay-afraid-to-offend-leonard-nimoy-with-transformers-family-reunion-offer/|title=Michael Bay Afraid to Offend Leonard Nimoy With Transformers Family Reunion Offer|last=Carroll|first=Larry|work=MoviesBlog.MTV.com|publisher=MTV|date=2009-04-21|accessdate=2010-07-03|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110220032538/http://moviesblog.mtv.com/2009/04/21/michael-bay-afraid-to-offend-leonard-nimoy-with-transformers-family-reunion-offer|archivedate=2011-02-20}}</ref> He attended the exclusive [[Crossroads School (Santa Monica)|Crossroads School]], in [[Santa Monica, California]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/may/24/entertainment/ca-transformers24|title=Michael Bay, master of the 'huge canvas'|last=Boucher|first=Geoff|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=[[Sam Zell]]|date=2009-05-24|accessdate=2010-07-03}}</ref> Bay often traces his interest in action films back to an incident during his childhood. As a boy, he attached some firecrackers to a toy train and filmed the ensuing fiery disaster with his mother's [[8 mm film|8 millimeter]] camera. The fire department was called and he was grounded.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/movies/news/2009-06-18-transformers-main_N.htm|title='Transformers' blasts back: Another Michael Bay direct hit|last=Breznican|first=Anthony|work=USA Today|publisher=[[Gannett Company]]|date=2009-06-18|accessdate=2010-07-03}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nBay got his start in the film industry interning with [[George Lucas]] when he was fifteen, filing the [[storyboards]] for ''[[Raiders of the Lost Ark]]'', which he thought was going to be terrible. His opinion changed after seeing it in the theater and he was so impressed by the experience that he decided to become a film director.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20035285_20035331_20044598,00.html|last=Vary|first=Adam B.|title=Optimus Prime Time|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=2010-06-30|accessdate=2010-07-04}}</ref> He graduated from [[Wesleyan University]] in 1986, majoring in both English and Film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.michaelbay.com/bio/bio.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080531091042/http://www.michaelbay.com/bio/bio.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2008-05-31|title=Biography|last=Lauren|first=Nelson|work=michaelbay.com|accessdate=2010-07-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/forbes/2009/0622/celebrity-09-transformers-michael-bay-making-movies-enemies-money.html|title=Michael Bay: Making Movies, Enemies and Money|page=2|last=Pomerantz|first=Dorothy|work=Forbes|publisher=[[Forbes]]|date=2009-06-22|accessdate=2010-07-03}}</ref> He was a member of the [[Psi Upsilon]] fraternity and a favorite student of film historian [[Jeanine Basinger]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.criterion.com/current/posts/48-armageddon|title=Armageddon|last=Basinger|first=Jeanine|work=The Criterion Collection|publisher=[[The Criterion Collection]]|date=1999-06-21|accessdate=2010-07-04}}</ref> For his graduate work, he attended [[Art Center College of Design]] in [[Pasadena, California|Pasadena]] where he also studied film.<ref name=\"educate\">{{cite web|title=Michael Bay- Biography|url=https://movies.yahoo.com/person/michael-bay/biography.html|publisher=[[Yahoo! Movies]]|accessdate=June 17, 2013}}</ref>\n\nMichael Bay began working at [[Propaganda Films]], directing commercials and music videos, two weeks after finishing his post-graduate degree.<ref name=\"educate\"/> His 90-second World War II-inspired [[Coca-Cola]] advertisement was picked up by [[Capitol Records]]. His first national commercial was for the [[Red Cross]], which won a [[Clio Awards|Clio Award]] in 1992.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,283851,00.html|title=Is Michael Bay the Devil?|last=Hochman|first=David|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=1998-07-10|accessdate=2010-07-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amctv.com/originals/shootout/smso_guests/biopage_bay|title=Shootout \u2013 Michael Bay|publisher=AMC TV|accessdate=2010-07-04|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100622075558/http://www.amctv.com/originals/shootout/smso_guests/biopage_bay|archivedate=2010-06-22}}</ref> He directed [[Goodby, Silverstein & Partners]] \"Got Milk?\" advertisement campaign for the California Milk Processors Board in 1993, which also won a Grand Prix Clio Award for Commercial of the Year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theinspirationroom.com/daily/2009/aaron-burr-got-milk/|title=Got Milk? (Aaron Burr)|work=The Inspiration Room|date=2009-05-15|accessdate=2010-07-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.indiewire.com/2013/04/the-best-commercials-music-videos-of-michael-bay-99069/|title=The Best Commercials & Music Videos Of Michael Bay|last=Staff|first=The Playlist|date=2013-04-23|work=IndieWire|access-date=2018-04-10|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nBay's success in music videos gained the attention of producers [[Jerry Bruckheimer]] and [[Don Simpson]], who selected him to direct his first feature-length film, ''[[Bad Boys (1995 film)|Bad Boys]]''. The film was shot in [[Miami]] in 1994 and starred [[Will Smith]] and [[Martin Lawrence]]. The action film proved to be a break-out role for Smith, who was segueing from television to films at that time. Shooting in Miami was a good experience for Bay, who would later own a home in the city and spend a great deal of time there.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hauteliving.com/2008/09/behind-the-camera-%60/|title=Behind the Camera|last=Wilson|first=Stephanie|work=Haute Living|publisher=Seth Semilof|date=2008-09-05|accessdate=2010-07-05|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111005043649/http://www.hauteliving.com/2008/09/behind-the-camera-%60/|archivedate=2011-10-05}}</ref> The film was completed for $19 million and grossed a remarkable $141 million at the box office in the summer of 1995.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worstpreviews.com/headline.php?id=17446|title=Martin Lawrence Says ''Bad Boys'' 3 is Real|work=Worst Previews.com|date=2010-04-21|accessdate=2010-07-05}}</ref> Bay's success led to a strong partnership and friendship with [[Jerry Bruckheimer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehollywoodinterview.blogspot.com/2008/02/jerry-bruckheimer-hollywood-interview.html|title=Jerry Bruckheimer: The Hollywood Interview|last=Simon|first=Alex|work=reprinted by The Hollywood Interview.com (originally published by Venice Magazine)|publisher=Nancy Martinez|date=2008-02-28 |origyear= June 2001|accessdate=2010-07-05}}</ref>\n\nHis follow-up film, ''[[The Rock (film)|The Rock]]'' (1996), was an action movie set on [[Alcatraz Island]], and in the [[San Francisco Bay area]]. It starred [[Sean Connery]], [[Nicolas Cage]] and [[Ed Harris]]. It was also produced by [[Jerry Bruckheimer]] and [[Don Simpson]], the latter of whom died five months before the film's release. The film is dedicated to him.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,291215,00.html|title=Death of a Hollywood Bad Boy|last=Ascher-Walsh|first=Rebecca|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=1996-02-06|accessdate=2010-07-06}}</ref> Connery and Cage won 'Best On-Screen Duo' at the [[MTV Movie Awards]] in 1997 and the film was nominated for an Academy Award in the Best Achievement in Sound category for the work of Greg P. Russell, [[Kevin O'Connell (sound re-recording mixer)|Kevin O'Connell]], and Keith A. Wester.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/ontv/movieawards/1997/|title=1997 MTV Movie Awards \u2013 Winners|publisher=MTV|date=1997-06-10|accessdate=2010-07-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/oscarlegacy/1990-1999/69nominees.html |title=Nominees and Winners for the 69th Annual Academy Awards |publisher=The Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences|date=1997-03-24 |accessdate=2010-07-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130723031146/http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/oscarlegacy/1990-1999/69nominees.html |archivedate=2013-07-23 }}</ref> After the success of The Rock, Bay established his production company Bay Films, with a two-picture deal with Disney.\n\n[[File:Michael Bay 060530-F-4692S-004.jpg|left|thumb|330px|Michael Bay on the set of ''Transformers'', New Mexico, May 2006]]\nIn 1998, Bay collaborated with [[Jerry Bruckheimer]] again, this time as a co-producer, as well as directing the action-adventure film ''[[Armageddon (1998 film)|Armageddon]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dvdreview.com/html/dvd_review_-_michael_bay_interview.shtml|title=DVD Review \u2013 Midas Touch of Destruction|last=Henckel|first=Guido|work=DVD Review|date=February 1999|accessdate=2010-07-09|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719085054/http://www.dvdreview.com/html/dvd_review_-_michael_bay_interview.shtml|archivedate=2011-07-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessweek.com/magazine/content/04_22/b3885110.htm|title=Jerry Bruckheimer: Hollywood's Most Wanted |last=Grover|first=Ronald|work=Businessweek \u2013 BW Online|publisher=[[McGraw-Hill]]|date=2004-05-31|accessdate=2010-07-09}}</ref> The film, about a group of tough oil drillers who are sent by [[NASA]] to deflect an [[asteroid]] away from a [[collision course]] with [[Earth]], starred [[Bruce Willis]], [[Billy Bob Thornton]], [[Ben Affleck]] and [[Liv Tyler]]. It was nominated for 4 [[Academy Awards|Oscars]] at the [[71st Academy Awards]] including [[Academy Award for Best Sound Mixing|Best Sound]], [[Academy Award for Best Visual Effects|Best Visual Effects]], [[Academy Award for Best Sound Editing|Best Sound Editing]], and [[Academy Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/oscarlegacy/1990-1999/71nominees.html |title=Nominees & Winners for the 71st Academy Awards |publisher=The Academy of Motion Picture Arts & Sciences|date=1999-03-21 |accessdate=2010-07-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102161927/http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/oscarlegacy/1990-1999/71nominees.html |archivedate=2013-11-02 }}</ref> The film earned 9.6 million dollars on its opening day and a total of 36.5 million through the first weekend.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=1056&p=s.htm|title=Daily Box Office: Mild, Mild West|last=Gray|first=Brandon|work=Box Office Mojo|date=1999-07-01|accessdate=2010-07-09}}</ref> The production budget, $140 million, was one of the highest of the summer of 1998. ''[[Armageddon (1998 film)|Armageddon]]'' went on to gross over $553 million worldwide, becoming the highest-grossing film of that year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=armageddon.htm|title=Armageddon (1998) \u2013 Box Office Mojo|date=1998-10-11|accessdate=2010-07-09}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001, Bay directed ''[[Pearl Harbor (film)|Pearl Harbor]]''. It starred [[Ben Affleck]], [[Josh Hartnett]], [[Kate Beckinsale]] and [[Cuba Gooding, Jr.]] The film was released on [[Memorial Day]] weekend in 2001. Again, Bay produced the film with Jerry Bruckheimer. The film received four Academy Award nominations, including Best Sound, Best Visual Effects, Best Sound Editing and Best Song. Again, Kevin O'Connell received another nomination for Best Sound, but he did not win. ''Pearl Harbor'' won in the category for Sound Editing, making it Bay's first (and, to date, only) film to win an Oscar.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/oscarlegacy/2000-2009/74nominees.html|title=Nominees and Winners for the 74th Annual Academy Awards|publisher=The Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences|date=2002-05-24|accessdate=2010-07-29}}</ref> Michael Bay also directed the music video for nominated track \"There You'll Be\" by vocal artist [[Faith Hill]].<ref name=\"educate\"/>\n\nBay reteamed with Will Smith and Martin Lawrence for ''[[Bad Boys II]]'', a sequel which also marked Bay's fifth collaboration with [[Jerry Bruckheimer]]. The film grossed $138 million domestically, enough to cover the production budget, and $273 million worldwide, almost twice as much as the first movie.\nIn 2005, Bay directed ''[[The Island (2005 film)|The Island]]'', a science fiction film starring [[Ewan McGregor]] and [[Scarlett Johansson]]. It was the first film Bay made without Jerry Bruckheimer as a producer. ''[[The Island (2005 film)|The Island]]'' cost $126 million to produce and earned $36 million domestically and $127 million overseas making a worldwide total of $163 million. Bay stated that he was not comfortable with the domestic marketing campaign, as it confused the audience to the true subject of the film.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2005/jul/17/entertainment/ca-michaelbay17|title=You Call This Paradise?|last=Horn|first=John|work=The Los Angeles Times|date=2005-07-17|accessdate=2010-07-11}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Michael Bay filming.jpg|thumb|right|Bay filming ''[[Transformers: Age of Extinction]]''; actresses Abigail Klein, Melanie Specht and [[Victoria Summer]] are walking in a corridor.]]\nIn 2007, he directed and teamed up with [[Steven Spielberg]] to produce ''[[Transformers (film)|Transformers]]'', a live action film based on the [[Transformers|''Transformers'' franchise]]. The film was released in the U.S. and Canada on July 3, 2007, with 8 p.m. preview screenings on July 2. The previews earned $8.8 million, and in its first day of general release it grossed $27.8 million, a record for Tuesday box office attendance.{{citation needed|date=April 2010}} It broke the record held by ''[[Spider-Man 2]]'' for the biggest July 4 gross, making $29 million. On its opening weekend, ''[[Transformers (film)|Transformers]]'' grossed $70.5 million, amounting to a $155.4 million opening week, giving it the record for the biggest opening week for a non-sequel.{{citation needed|date=July 2010}} As of November 2007, the film has made over $319 million domestically and over $709 million worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=transformers06.htm|title=Transformers (2007) - Box Office Mojo|website=www.boxofficemojo.com}}</ref> Bay returned as director and executive producer for ''[[Transformers: Revenge of the Fallen]]'', which was released on June 24, 2009 and went on to gross over $832 million worldwide. Although it received mostly negative reviews by critics,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/transformers_revenge_of_the_fallen/|title=Transformers: Revenge of the Fallen|publisher=}}</ref> including aggressively critical reviews by American film critics such as [[Roger Ebert]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20090623/REVIEWS/906239997|title=Reviews \u2013 Transformers 2: Revenge of the Fallen|last=Ebert|first=Roger|work=[[Roger Ebert]]|date=2010-06-23|accessdate=2010-08-25}}</ref> [[Michael Phillips (critic)|Michael Phillips]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/chicagotribune/access/1758804881.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jun+24%2C+2009&author=Michael+Phillips&pub=Chicago+Tribune&edition=&startpage=1&desc=And+the+popcorn+transforms+into+earqplugs|title=And the popcorn transforms into earqplugs|last=Philips|first=Michael|work=Live!|publisher=Chicago Tribune|date=2009-06-24|accessdate=2010-08-25}}</ref> and [[David Denby (film critic)|David Denby]] (who referred to Bay as \"stunningly, almost viciously, untalented\"),<ref name=\"Denby\">{{cite web|url=http://www.newyorker.com/arts/critics/cinema/2009/07/06/090706crci_cinema_denby?currentPage=2|last=Denby|first=David|title=Tommy Guns and Toys|work=The New Yorker|publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast Publications]]|date=2009-07-06|accessdate=2010-08-25}}</ref> the film was well received by its intended audience and was one of the highest-grossing films of 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.askmen.com/entertainment/movie/transformers-revenge-of-the-fallen.html|title=The AM Take|last=Nusair|first=David|work=AskMen.com|date=2009-06-26|accessdate=2010-08-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/arts/article/0,8599,1906689,00.html|title=Transformers: Revenge of the Fallen Falls Short|last=Pols|first=Mary|work=Time|publisher=[[Time Warner]]|date=2009-06-24|accessdate=2010-08-25}}</ref> In 2010, it earned seven [[Golden Raspberry Award]] nominations and winning three: [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Picture|Worst Picture]], [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Director|Worst Director]] and [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Screenplay|Worst Screenplay]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.razzies.com/history/09release.asp|title=30th Annual Dis-Honors for Cinematic Dreck: RAZZIE Voters Spread the Loathe Around|work=[[Golden Raspberry Awards]]|date=2010-03-06|accessdate=2010-08-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160922035636/http://www.razzies.com/history/09release.asp|archive-date=2016-09-22|url-status=dead}}</ref> It was also one of the best selling DVD and Blu-ray Discs of 2009, second only to Twilight in DVD format and the number one of all time in [[Blu-ray Disc|Blu-ray]] format until it was surpassed by Blu-ray sales of [[James Cameron]]'s ''[[Avatar (2009 film)|Avatar]]'' in April 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-numbers.com/dvd/charts/annual/2009.php|title=Top-Selling DVDs of 2009|work=The Numbers|publisher=Nash Information Services, LLC.|date=2010-08-31|accessdate=2010-08-31}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hd.engadget.com/2009/10/29/transformers-2-tops-chart-best-selling-blu-ray-of-all-time/|title=Transformers 2 tops chart, best selling Blu-ray of all time?|last=Drawbaugh|first=Ben|work=[[Engadget]]|date=2010-10-29|accessdate=2010-08-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091125015340/http://hd.engadget.com/2009/10/29/transformers-2-tops-chart-best-selling-blu-ray-of-all-time/|archive-date=November 25, 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hd.engadget.com/2010/04/26/avatar-smashes-blu-ray-sales-records-has-some-owners-ready-to-s/|title=Avatar smashes Blu-ray sales records, has some owners ready to smash incompatible players|last=Lawler|first=Richard|work=[[Engadget]]|date=2010-04-26|accessdate=2010-04-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100429143658/http://hd.engadget.com/2010/04/26/avatar-smashes-blu-ray-sales-records-has-some-owners-ready-to-s|archive-date=April 29, 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>\nBay directed ''[[Transformers: Dark of the Moon]]'', released on June 28, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thefilmstage.com/2009/10/01/transformers-3-set-for-2011/|title=Transformers 3 Set for 2011 at The Film Stage|last=Barr|first=Merrill|work=The Film Stage|date=2010-01-09|accessdate=2010-09-02|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100826121656/http://thefilmstage.com/2009/10/01/transformers-3-set-for-2011/|archivedate=2010-08-26}}</ref> which went on to gross $1.123 billion globally.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=transformers3.htm|title=Transformers: Dark of the Moon (2011) - Box Office Mojo|website=www.boxofficemojo.com}}</ref> His next film was a comparatively small film he had been developing for years, called ''[[Pain & Gain]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.michaelbay.com/newsblog/files/0fd64fd57c9b9b6d33e15c76a46dae48-565.html|title=Transformers 3, Pain & Gain, Bad Boys 3|last=Lauren|first=Nelson|work=michaelbay.com|date=2009-09-13|accessdate=2010-06-16|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091012210851/http://www.michaelbay.com/newsblog/files/0fd64fd57c9b9b6d33e15c76a46dae48-565.html|archivedate=2009-10-12}}</ref> The [[true crime]] story, based on events described in a ''[[Miami New Times]]'' article<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.miaminewtimes.com/1999-12-23/news/pain-gain|title=Pain & Gain|last=Collins|first=Pete|work=[[Miami New Times]]|publisher=Kevin Thornburg|date=1999-12-23|accessdate=2010-09-02}}</ref> written by Pete Collins, concerns a group of bumbling bodybuilders working together to commit a robbery.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2439620/transformers-dark-of-the-moon-michael-bay-taylor-lautner-bad-boys-3/|title='Transformers' Director Michael Bay On His Next Movie, Taylor Lautner And 'Bad Boys 3'|first=Josh|last=Wigler|website=MTV News}}</ref> It starred [[Mark Wahlberg]], [[Dwayne Johnson]], [[Anthony Mackie]], [[Tony Shalhoub]] and [[Ed Harris]].\n\nBay produced [[DreamWorks Pictures|DreamWorks]]' ''[[I Am Number Four (film)|I Am Number Four]]'', based on a series of novels by [[Pittacus Lore]] published by [[HarperCollins]] Children's Books. [[D. J. Caruso]] (''[[Eagle Eye]]'', ''[[Disturbia (film)|Disturbia]]'') directed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSTRE60J22I20100120|title=\"Disturbia\" director counts on \"Four\"|last=Kit|first=Borys|work=[[Reuters]]|date=2010-01-20|accessdate=2010-09-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/07/01/harpercollins-buys-series-from-james-frey/|title=HarperCollins Buys Series From James Frey|last=Motoko|first=Rich|work=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=Sulzberger family|date=2009-07-01|accessdate=2010-09-02}}</ref>\n\nA fourth Bay-directed Transformers movie, ''[[Transformers: Age of Extinction]]'', was released in June 2014.<ref name=\"June2014\">[http://marquee.blogs.cnn.com/2012/02/14/transformers-4-arriving-in-june-2014/ 'Transformers 4' arriving in June 2014], CNN, February 14, 2012.</ref> Starring [[Mark Wahlberg]], the film earned $1.1 billion at the global box office <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=transformers4.htm|title=Transformers: Age of Extinction (2014) - Box Office Mojo|website=www.boxofficemojo.com}}</ref> On January 12, 2016, [[Paramount Pictures]] released ''[[13 Hours]]'', which Bay produced and directed, based on the [[2012 Benghazi attack]]. While being the lowest-grossing film at the box office of Bay's career, it went on to massive DVD sales upon its digital release in May 2016, earning over $40 million in home video revenue.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/michael-bays-benghazi-film-gets-916588 |title=Michael Bay's Benghazi Film Gets Trump Bump in Home Video}}</ref>\n\nOn May 23, 2017, Bay was honored with his own Hand and Footprint Ceremony at The TCL Chinese Theatre. His English Mastiff, Rebel, also put her paw in the cement with Bay.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/features/michael-bay-hands-and-feet-honor-1202440033/|title=Michael Bay Reflects on His Career as He Receives Hands and Feet Honor|last=Riley|first=Jenelle|date=2017-05-23|work=Variety|access-date=2017-11-22|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, it was announced that Bay would direct the [[Netflix]] action thriller film ''[[6 Underground (film)|6 Underground]]'', starring [[Ryan Reynolds]].<ref name=\"D'Alessandro\"/> The film was released on December 13, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/video/6-underground-trailer-ryan-reynolds-michael-bay-netflix/|title=\u20186 Underground\u2019 Trailer: Ryan Reynolds Sums It Up \u2013 \u201cThis Is All So [Bleeping] Dangerous\u201d|last=Hipes|first=Patrick|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=October 1, 2019|access-date=February 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Production and effects companies==\n\n===Platinum Dunes===\n{{main|Platinum Dunes}}\nBay founded production house [[Platinum Dunes]] with fellow producers Brad Fuller and Andrew Form in 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/platinumdunes/ |title=Platinum Dunes: The Official Site |last=Fuller |first=Brad |work=Bloody Disgusting |publisher=[[Bloody Disgusting|Brad Miska and Tom Owen]] |date=2009-12-21 |accessdate=2010-09-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080612181840/http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/platinumdunes/ |archivedate=2008-06-12 }}</ref>\n\n===Digital Domain===\n{{main|Digital Domain}}\nBay and Wyndcrest Holdings, a Florida-based investment firm, acquired the [[Visual effects|digital effects]] company [[Digital Domain]] from [[James Cameron]] and [[Stan Winston]] in 2006, infusing the struggling business with a $50 million investment. Digital Domain considered an [[initial public offering]] in 2009 but ultimately withdrew the offer, because of the lack of interest. The company was sold to Galloping Horse in 2012.\n\n===The Institute===\nAfter leaving [[Propaganda Films]], Bay and producer [[Scott Gardenhour]], also formerly at Propaganda, formed The Institute for the Development of Enhanced Perceptual Awareness (now known as [[The Institute (production company)|The Institute]]), to produce commercials and other projects. Through The Institute, Bay has directed and produced spots for [[Victoria's Secret]], [[Lexus]], [[Budweiser (Anheuser-Busch)|Budweiser]], [[Reebok]], [[Mercedes-Benz]], and [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]]. One of his Victoria Secret ads was for the 2009 \"A Thousand Fantasies\" holiday campaign.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://vimeo.com/8083470|title=Victoria&#039;s Secret &quot;A Thousand Fantasies&quot; (90 sec)|first=Michael Bay Dot|last=Com|date=9 December 2009|publisher=|via=Vimeo}}</ref>\n\n===451 Media Group===\nBay co-founded 451 Media Group with Doug Nunes (who serves as CEO), and with John and Anthony Gentile, who previously marketed brands such as [[Micronauts]], ''[[Visionaries: Knights of the Magical Light|Visionaries]]'', [[Sky Dancers]] and the [[Power Glove]]. In 2015, the company announced an interactive publishing division to offer \"[[augmented reality]]\" content from printed graphic novels with digital video. The graphic novels employ Touchcode technology from T+ink (previously used in the Power Glove), in which ink used in the printing process unlocks access to exclusive content that is housed on the [[Machinima Network]], which is transferred to users' touch-screen-enabled mobile devices when the printed books are touched to those devices. The company's premiere slate of graphic novels was unveiled at the October 2015 [[New York Comic-Con]]. The creators involved included [[Scott Rosenberg]], [[Skip Woods]], [[George Pelecanos]], Mark Mallouk, Clay McLeod Chapman and Peter and Paul Williams.<ref>McNary, Dave (August 25, 2015). [https://variety.com/2015/film/news/michael-bay-451-media-group-interactive-arm-1201577517/ \"Michael Bay\u2019s 451 Media Group Launching Interactive Publishing Arm\"]. ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]''.</ref><ref>Wickline, Dan (August 25, 2015). [http://www.bleedingcool.com/2015/08/25/michael-bays-451-media-group-to-publish-hi-tech-graphic-novels/ \"Michael Bay\u2019s 451 Media Group To Publish Hi-Tech Graphic Novels\"]. ''[[Bleeding Cool]]''.</ref><ref>Damore, Meagan (August 25, 2015). [http://www.comicbookresources.com/article/michael-bays-451-media-group-announces-interactive-graphic-novels \"Michael Bay's 451 Media Group Announces Interactive Graphic Novels\"]. [[Comic Book Resources]].</ref><ref>Kamen, Matt (August 26, 2015). [https://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2015-08/26/michael-bay-digital-comics-graphic-novels \"Michael Bay is launching a range of 'augmented reality comics'\"]. ''[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]''.</ref>\n\n===Rogue Initiative===\nIn June 2016, Bay joined The Rogue Initiative,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.digitaltrends.com/virtual-reality/michael-bay-the-rogue-initiative/|title=VR explosions are en route as Michael Bay teams with The Rogue Initiative|date=21 June 2016|publisher=}}</ref> a production studio and technology company, as a strategic advisor and stakeholder. The studio merges Hollywood production with interactive talent to generate story-driven content for games, mobile, virtual reality, mixed reality, television and feature film. As part of the partnership, Bay will develop and direct a multiplatform action-adventure game and cinematic VR experiences, based on an original IP conceived by him.\n\n==Personal life==\nBay lives in [[Miami]] with his three [[English mastiff]]s, named for characters in his films. As a boy, he donated his [[Bar Mitzvah]] money to an [[animal shelter]] and often includes his dogs in his films. Bonecrusher appeared as Mikaela's dog \"Bones\" in ''[[Transformers: Revenge of the Fallen]]''. Mason, his first English mastiff, was named for John Patrick Mason, played by [[Sean Connery]] in ''[[The Rock (film)|The Rock]]''.<ref name = \"NYT\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/07/17/garden/at-home-with-michael-bay-a-slam-bang-master-with-a-house-of-om.html|title=AT HOME WITH \u2013 Michael Bay \u2013 A Slam-Bang Master with a House of Om|last=Diamond|first=Jamie|work=The New York Times|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|date=2003-07-17|accessdate=2010-07-04}}</ref> Mason appeared as Marcus' dog in ''[[Bad Boys II]]'' and as Miles' dog in ''[[Transformers (film)|Transformers]]''. He died during production of the latter film in March 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.michaelbay.com/newsblog/files/53720902344ff50ba68da26d558aacb0-71.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090106034142/http://michaelbay.com/newsblog/files/53720902344ff50ba68da26d558aacb0-71.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2009-01-06|title=Sunday Post|last=Lauren|first=Nelson|work=michaelbay.com|date=2007-05-06|accessdate=2010-07-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1504631/|title=Mason Rock Bay|work=IMDb|accessdate=2010-07-04}}</ref>\n\nBay is not married and has no children.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2011/dirt/real-estalker/michael-bay-bails-in-montecito-1201231949/|title=Michael Bay Bails in Montecito|first=Mark|last=David|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=September 6, 2011|accessdate=September 4, 2019}}</ref> He previously dated sportscaster [[Lisa Dergan]].<ref name = \"NYT\" />\n\n==Filmography==\n{{Main|Michael Bay filmography}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-  style=\"background:#b0c4de; text-align:center;\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Producers\n! Writers\n! Studio \n! Budget \n! Box office\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''[[Bad Boys (1995 film)|Bad Boys]]''\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Jerry Bruckheimer]] and [[Don Simpson]]\n| Michael Barrie, [[Jim Mulholland]], [[Doug Richardson]] and [[George Gallo]] \n| [[Columbia Pictures]]\n| $19 million \n| $141.4 million \n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[The Rock (film)|The Rock]]''\n| [[David Weisberg]], [[Douglas S. Cook]] and Mark Rosner \n| [[Buena Vista Pictures]]\n| $75 million \n| $335.1 million \n|-\n| 1998\n| ''[[Armageddon (1998 film)|Armageddon]]''\n| Jerry Bruckheimer and [[Gale Anne Hurd]] \n| [[Tony Gilroy]], [[Shane Salerno]], [[Jonathan Hensleigh]], [[J. J. Abrams]] and [[Robert Roy Pool]] \n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Touchstone Pictures]]<br>Buena Vista Pictures\n| $140 million\n| $553.7 million\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''[[Pearl Harbor (film)|Pearl Harbor]]''\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Jerry Bruckheimer\n| [[Randall Wallace]]\n| $140 million\n| $449.2 million\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''[[Bad Boys II]]''\n| [[Ron Shelton]], [[Jerry Stahl]], [[Cormac Wibberley and Marianne Wibberley|Cormac Wibberley, Marianne Wibberley]] and Ron Shelton\n| Columbia Pictures\n| $130 million\n| $273.3 million\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[The Island (2005 film)|The Island]]''\n| [[Ian Bryce]] and [[Walter F. Parkes]]\n| Caspian Tredwell-Owen, [[Alex Kurtzman]] and [[Roberto Orci]]\n| [[DreamWorks Pictures]]<br>[[Warner Bros.]]\n| $126 million\n| $162.9 million\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[