ese]]\n| narrator       = \n| music          = [[Ramesh Narayan]]\n| cinematography = [[Ravi Varman]]\n| editing        = \n| studio         = Nirmalyam Cinema\n| distributor    = Pallavi Release\n| released       =\n| runtime        = \n| country        = India\n| language       = Malayalam\n| budget         = <!--Do not add without providing a source that has a reputation for fact checking and editorial oversight.-->\n| gross          = <!--Do not add without providing a source that has a reputation for fact checking and editorial oversight.-->\n}}\n\n'''''Kolaambi ''''' ({{translation|Loudspeaker}}) is an upcoming Indian [[Malayalam]]-language [[Drama (film and television)|drama film]] written and directed by [[T. K. Rajeev Kumar]], starring [[Nithya Menen]], [[Renji Panicker]], [[Sijoy Varghese]] and [[Dileesh Pothan]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsbugz.com/kolambi-malayalam-movie/|title=Kolambi Malayalam Movie (2019) {{!}} Cast {{!}} Teaser {{!}} Trailer {{!}} Release Date|last=Agatheeswaran|date=2019-06-04|website=News Bugz|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190620085301/https://www.newsbugz.com/kolambi-malayalam-movie/|archive-date=20 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The film is produced by Roopesh Omana under the production house Nirmalyam Cinema. [[Resul Pookutty]] handles the sound recording, while music is composed by [[Ramesh Narayan]] and cinematography is done by [[Ravi Varman]].<ref>{{cite web | last=Native | first=Digital | title=Nithya Menen to team up with Rajeev Kumar for 'Kolambi' | website=The News Minute | date=26 November 2018 | url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/nithya-menen-team-rajeev-kumar-kolambi-92259 | access-date=7 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/malayalam/movies/news/kolambi-trailer-magnificient-visuals-combined-with-effective-storytelling/articleshow/69650631.cms|title='Kolambi' trailer: Magnificient visuals combined with effective storytelling|date=4 June 2019|newspaper=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2019-06-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190610043718/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/malayalam/movies/news/kolambi-trailer-magnificient-visuals-combined-with-effective-storytelling/articleshow/69650631.cms|archive-date=10 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Production design is done by [[Sabu Cyril]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://malayalam.indianexpress.com/entertainment/kolambi-movie-trailer-released-nithya-menon-and-ranji-panicker-shines-264189/|title=\u0d09\u0d1a\u0d4d\u0d1a\u0d2d\u0d3e\u0d37\u0d3f\u0d23\u0d3f\u0d15\u0d33\u0d41\u0d1f\u0d46 \u0d15\u0d3e\u0d32\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d24\u0d47\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d4d \u0d28\u0d3f\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d2f \u0d2e\u0d47\u0d28\u0d28\u0d4d\u0d31\u0d46 \u2018\u0d15\u0d4b\u0d33\u0d3e\u0d2e\u0d4d\u0d2a\u0d3f\u2019; \u0d1e\u0d46\u0d1f\u0d4d\u0d1f\u0d3f\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d41\u0d28\u0d4d\u0d28 \u0d17\u0d46\u0d31\u0d4d\u0d31\u0d2a\u0d4d\u0d2a\u0d3f\u0d32\u0d4d\u200d \u0d30\u0d1e\u0d4d\u0d1c\u0d3f \u0d2a\u0d23\u0d3f\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d30\u0d4d\u200d|date=2019-06-03|website=Indian Express Malayalam|language=ml|access-date=2019-06-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190620091857/https://malayalam.indianexpress.com/entertainment/kolambi-movie-trailer-released-nithya-menon-and-ranji-panicker-shines-264189/|archive-date=20 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n''Kolaambi'' was selected in Indian Panorama, at 50th [[International Film Festival of India|\nInternational Film Festival of India (IFFI)]], Goa, held from 20 November to 28. It was premiered at the festival.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mathrubhumi.com/movies-music/news/iffi-goa-2019-uyare-jallikkattu-kolambi-selected-to-indian-panorama-1.4176666|title=50-\u0d3e\u0d2e\u0d24\u0d4d \u0d17\u0d4b\u0d35 \u0d1a\u0d32\u0d1a\u0d4d\u0d1a\u0d3f\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d30\u0d2e\u0d47\u0d33\u0d2f\u0d3f\u0d32\u0d47\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d4d \u0d09\u0d2f\u0d30\u0d46\u0d2f\u0d41\u0d02 \u0d15\u0d4b\u0d33\u0d3e\u0d2e\u0d4d\u0d2a\u0d3f\u0d2f\u0d41\u0d02 \u0d1c\u0d32\u0d4d\u0d32\u0d3f\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d46\u0d1f\u0d4d\u0d1f\u0d41\u0d02|website=Mathrubhumi|language=ml|access-date=2019-10-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.manoramaonline.com/news/latest-news/2019/10/06/iffi-2019-three-malayalam-movies-selected-to-indian-panorama.html|title=\u0d09\u0d2f\u0d30\u0d46\u0d2f\u0d41\u0d02 \u0d1c\u0d32\u0d4d\u0d32\u0d3f\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d46\u0d1f\u0d4d\u0d1f\u0d41\u0d02 \u0d15\u0d4b\u0d33\u0d3e\u0d2e\u0d4d\u0d2a\u0d3f\u0d2f\u0d41\u0d02 \u0d30\u0d3e\u0d1c\u0d4d\u0d2f\u0d3e\u0d28\u0d4d\u0d24\u0d30 \u0d2e\u0d47\u0d33\u0d2f\u0d3f\u0d7d; \u0d07\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d24\u0d35\u0d23 \u0d38\u0d3f\u0d28\u0d3f\u0d2e \u2018\u0d15\u0d47\u0d7e\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d3e\u0d02\u2019|website=www.manoramaonline.com|language=ml|access-date=2019-10-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://english.manoramaonline.com/entertainment/entertainment-news/2019/10/06/malayalam-movies-iffi-priyadarshan-goa.html|title='Jallikattu', 'Uyare' and 'Kolambi' to be screened at 50th IFFI in Goa|website=OnManorama}}</ref>\n\n== Cast ==\n<!--As this film has not yet been released, additions to this section must be sourced, per WP:CRYSTAL.-->\n* [[Nithya Menon]] as Arundhati\n* [[Renji Panicker]]\n* [[Dileesh Pothan]] as Bank Manager\n* [[Sijoy Varghese]] as Sanjay Tharakan\n* [[Rohini (actress)|Rohini]] as Sundarambal\n* [[Aristo Suresh]] as Aampli Naanu\n* [[Siddharth Menon]] as Solomon\n* [[Baiju Santhosh]] as Moulavi\n* [[Vijay Yesudas]]\n* [[Manju Pillai]] as Lawyer\n* Suresh Kumar as Varghese\n* [[P. Balachandran]] as Kamal Pasha\n* [[Pauly Valsan]] as Alphonse\n* [[Jayakrishnan]]\n* [[Asha Aravind]]\n\n==Production==\nKolaambi marks the 25th film and directorial come back of director T. K Rajeev Kumar after  nearly 6 years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.manoramaonline.com/movies/movie-news/2018/10/17/t-k-rajeev-kumar-come-back-with-new-movie-nithya-menon.html|title=\u0d30\u0d4b\u0d17\u0d19\u0d4d\u0d19\u0d33\u0d4b\u0d1f\u0d4d \u0d2a\u0d3e\u0d2f\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d2a\u0d4d\u0d2a\u0d4d; \u0d2a\u0d41\u0d24\u0d3f\u0d2f \u0d1a\u0d3f\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d30\u0d35\u0d41\u0d2e\u0d3e\u0d2f\u0d3f \u0d1f\u0d3f.\u0d15\u0d46. \u0d30\u0d3e\u0d1c\u0d40\u0d35\u0d4d \u0d15\u0d41\u0d2e\u0d3e\u0d30\u0d4d\u200d|website=ManoramaOnline|access-date=2019-10-06}}</ref> [[Resul Pookutty]] was roped in to do sound recording. [[Ravi Varman]] was signed as the cinematographer and [[Sabu Cyril]] as the production designer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cms.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/malayalam/2018/oct/24/nithya-menen-in-t-k-rajeev-kumars-next-kolambi-1889096.html|title=Nithya Menen in T K Rajeev Kumar\u2019s next, Kolambi|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2019-10-06}}</ref> Nithya Menen was roped in to do the role of biennale artist, marks her second collaboration with [[T. K. Rajeev Kumar]] after ''[[Thalsamayam Oru Penkutty]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/nithya-menen-team-rajeev-kumar-kolambi-92259?amp|title=Nithya Menen to team up with Rajeev Kumar for 'Kolambi'|last=|first=|date=|website=www.thenewsminute.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-06}}</ref>\n\nPrincipal photography of the film was commenced at [[Thiruvananthapuram|Thiruvanathapuram]] on 18 October 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/malayalam/movies/nithya-menens-next-malayalam-film-is-kolambi/articleshow/66347294.cms|title=Nithya Menen's next Malayalam film is Kolambi - Times of India|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2019-10-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://m.cinemaexpress.com/article/nithya-menen-in-tk-rajeev-kumars-next-kolambi/8447/amp|title=Nithya Menen in\u00a0TK Rajeev Kumar\u2019s next, Kolambi {{!}} cinemaexpress|website=m.cinemaexpress.com|access-date=2019-10-06}}</ref>\n\n== Marketing ==\nThe trailer of the film was released on 3 June 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/malayalam/kolambi-trailer-nithya-menon-promises-a-feel-good-nostalgic-film-5763079/|title=Kolambi trailer: Nithya Menon promises a feel-good nostalgic film|date=2019-06-03|website=The Indian Express|language=en-IN|access-date=2019-06-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190621070317/https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/malayalam/kolambi-trailer-nithya-menon-promises-a-feel-good-nostalgic-film-5763079/|archive-date=21 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nowrunning.com/movie/23264/malayalam/kolambi/|title=Kolambi (2019) \u2013 Kolambi Malayalam Movie|website=NOWRUNNING|language=en|access-date=2019-06-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190621070319/https://www.nowrunning.com/movie/23264/malayalam/kolambi/|archive-date=21 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The animation teaser of the film was released on 24 July 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pinkvilla.com/entertainment/south/nithya-menen-starrer-kolambi-releases-its-animation-teaser-watch-video-463537|title=Nithya Menen starrer Kolambi releases its animation teaser; Watch Video|website=PINKVILLA|language=en|access-date=2019-07-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724180634/http://www.pinkvilla.com/entertainment/south/nithya-menen-starrer-kolambi-releases-its-animation-teaser-watch-video-463537|archive-date=24 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://boxofficeindia.co.in/nithya-menen-starrer-kolambi%E2%80%98s-animation-teaser-unmissable-%E2%80%93watch-here|title=Nithya Menen starrer Kolambi\u2018s animation teaser is unmissable \u2013watch here|date=2019-07-24|website=Box Office India|language=en|access-date=2019-07-24}}</ref>\n\n== Soundtrack ==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Kolaambi\n| type       = [[Soundtrack]]\n| artist     = [[Ramesh Narayan]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = 5 August 2019\n| recorded   = 2018-19\n| venue      =\n| studio     = Muzik Lounge, Chennai\n| genre      = [[Feature film soundtrack]]\n| length     = \n| language   = Malayalam\n| label      = [[Manorama Music]]\n| producer   = \n| prev_title = [[Ennu Ninte Moideen]]\n| prev_year  = 2015\n| next_title = \n| next_year  =\n| misc       =\n}}\n\n{{Tracklist\n| headline     = Track list\n|total_length  =\n| extra_column = Singer(s)\n| title1  = Aarodum Parayuka\n| lyrics1 = [[Prabha Varma]] \n| extra1  = [[Madhushree Narayan]]\n| length1 = 3:46\n| title2  = Ororo Novin\n| lyrics2 = [[Prabha Varma]]\n| extra2  = [[Bombay Jayashri]]\n| length2 = 4:45\n}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|9182478}}\n\n[[Category:Upcoming films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Malayalam-language films]]\n[[Category:Indian musical films]]\n[[Category:2010s Malayalam-language films]]\n[[Category:2010s drama films]]\n[[Category:Upcoming Malayalam-language films]] \n[[Category:Upcoming Indian films]]\n", "name_user": "Will Sandberg", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kolaambi"}
{"title_page": "Birgit Kober", "text_new": "{{short description|German Paralympic athlete}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name = Birgit Kober\n| image =2013-04 Birgit Kober.jpg\n| imagesize = <!-- Only for images narrower than 220 pixels -->\n| caption = Kober in April 2013.\n| nationality =[[Germany|German]]\n| sport = [[Track and Field]]\n| event  = [[shot put]]<br/>[[Javelin throw]]\n| club = TSV Bayer 04 Leverkusen\n| collegeteam = \n| coach = Joachim Lipske\n| birth_date ={{Birth date and age|1971|07|10|df=y}}\n| disability= [[Ataxia]]\n| birth_place = [[Munich]], [[West Germany]]\n| residence = \n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| height = \n| weight = \n| website = {{URL|https://www.birgitkober.de/}}\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalSport | Women's [[para athletics]]}}\n{{MedalCountry |{{GER}} }}\n{{MedalCount\n|[[Summer Paralympic Games|Paralympic Games]]|3|0|0\n|[[IPC Athletics World Championships|World Championships]]|4|0|0\n|[[IPC Athletics European Championships|European Championships]]|5|0|0\n}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[File:IPC logo (2004).svg|25px]] [[Paralympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2012 Summer Paralympics|2012 London]] | [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's shot put|Shot put F33/34]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2012 Summer Paralympics|2012 London]]|[[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's javelin throw|Javelin - F33/34/52/53]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2016 Summer Paralympics|2016 Rio de Janeiro]]|[[Athletics at the 2016 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's shot put|Shot put - F36]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[File:IPC logo (2004).svg|25px]] [[IPC Athletics World Championships|IPC World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold|{{nowrap|[[2011 Athletics World Championships|2011 Christchurch]]}}|[[2011 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's shot put|Shot put - F33/34]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2011 Athletics World Championships|2011 Christchurch]]|[[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's javelin throw|Javelin F33/34/52/53]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships|2013 Lyon]] |[[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's shot put|Shot put - F32/33/34]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships|2013 Lyon]] |[[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's javelin throw|Javelin F33/34]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[File:IPC logo (2004).svg|25px]] [[IPC Athletics European Championships|IPC European Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2012 IPC Athletics European Championships|2012 Stadskanaal]]|[[2012 IPC Athletics European Championships \u2013 Women's shot put|Shot put - F34]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2012 IPC Athletics European Championships|2012 Stadskanaal]]|[[2012 IPC Athletics European Championships \u2013 Women's javelin throw|Javelin F33/34/52/53]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2014 IPC Athletics European Championships|2014 Swansea]]|[[2014 IPC Athletics European Championships \u2013 Women's javelin throw|Javelin F34]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2014 IPC Athletics European Championships|2014 Swansea]]|[[2014 IPC Athletics European Championships \u2013 Women's shot put|shot put F34]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2016 IPC Athletics European Championships|2016 Grosseto]]|[[2016 IPC Athletics European Championships \u2013 Women's shot put|shot put F35/36]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Birgit Kober''' (born 10 July 1971) is a German Paralympic athlete.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ipc.infostradasports.com/asp/lib/TheASP.asp?pageid=8937&sportid=-1&personid=866545|title=Kober, Birgit|publisher=IPC Athletics|accessdate=9 August 2013}}</ref> She initially competed in [[T34 (classification)|F34]] seated throwing events, and from 2011-2013 she became the reigning champion at European, World and Paralympic level in both shot put and javelin in her class. At the [[2012 Summer Paralympic Games]] in London, she broke the world record in both her events. Following changes to the [[International Paralympic Committee|IPC]] rules for seated throws in 2014, she chose to compete in a standing position as an [[T36 (classification)|F36]] athlete.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kugelsto\u00dfen mit Birgit Kober \"Nimm die H\u00fcfte mit\"|url=http://www.spiegel.de/gesundheit/ernaehrung/paralympics-kugelstossen-mit-birgit-kober-a-1110340.html|publisher=Der Spiegel|date=16 September 2016|language=German}}</ref> She won the F36 shot put at the [[2016 Summer Paralympic Games]] with a Paralympic record throw. {{As of|April 2017}} she is World Record holder in the Women's F36 shot put, a distance of 11.52 m set in July 2016.<ref>[https://db.ipc-services.org/sdms/web/record/at/pdf/type/WR/category/out/gender/W/evt/SHO  Para Athletics World Records - Women's Shot Put]</ref><ref>[http://www.parasport-news.com/looking-towards-athletics-in-rio-t36-womens-world-records/11001/ Looking towards athletics in Rio: T36 women's world records]</ref>\n\n==Career history==\n===Early history===\nKober was born in 1971 and grew up in [[Munich]]. She took to sport at a young age, and by 14 she was involved in athletics and the javelin throw while at school in Munich. At the age of 16 a reaction with medical treatment left her deaf, and a year later she suffered an [[epileptic]] seizure. While still a teenager she moved to the Ruhr region where she attended a school for the deaf. She continued her education, specializing in medicine but was forced to cut her studies in 2006 to help care for her sick mother. In 2007 Kober suffered from a [[status epilepticus]] and she was rushed to hospital, but after complications she was left with [[ataxia]].\n\n===Athletics career===\nKober returned to athletics in 2008, mainly as a form of enjoyment with no serious ambitions to take the sport further. She joined [[TSV Bayer 04 Leverkusen]] where she was coached by Joachim Lipske. Kober was quickly identified as a potential talent in throwing events and by 2009 she was competing in national competitions. Classified as a T/F34 category para-athlete, Kober specialized in both the javelin and shot put. She qualified for the [[2011 IPC Athletics World Championships]] in Christchurch, New Zealand, and took gold in both her events. In the shot put, where she competed in a mixed F32/33/34 grouping, she threw a distance of 9.30m, a new world record.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://germanz.co.nz/archiv/ipc-international-paralympic-committee-wm-2011-in-christchurch-neuseeland-2-tag/|title=IPC (International Paralympic Committee) World Cup 2011 in Christchurch, New Zealand - 2  Day|language=German|date=24 January 2011|accessdate=9 August 2013|publisher=germanz.co.nz|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130208185819/http://germanz.co.nz/archiv/ipc-international-paralympic-committee-wm-2011-in-christchurch-neuseeland-2-tag/|archivedate=8 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, in the build-up to the [[2012 Summer Paralympics|Summer Paralympics in London]], she entered the [[2012 IPC Athletics European Championships|European Championships]] in [[Stadskanaal]] in the Netherlands. She again dominated the field taking both gold medals and recording a world record in the shot put with a throw of 10.06m.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ipcat.msl.es/ZBB101A_AT@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@ENG_number=7600.htm|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130809092650/http://ipcat.msl.es/ZBB101A_AT@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@ENG_number=7600.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=9 August 2013|title=Kober, Birgit|accessdate=9 August 2013|publisher=ipcat.msl.es}}</ref> At the Paralympics she recorded a distance of 27.03m in the javelin and three days later she threw 10.25m in the shot put. Both distances were new world records in the F34 classification and gave her gold in both events.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southafrica.info/news/sport/paralympics-040912.htm#.UgSv10VwbIU|title=SA improves on Paralympics medal tally|date=4 September 2012|first=Brad|last=Morgan|accessdate=9 August 2013|publisher=southafrica.info|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140114153810/http://www.southafrica.info/news/sport/paralympics-040912.htm#.UgSv10VwbIU|archive-date=14 January 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.athletics.com.au/home/news/news/2012/september/paralympics_ladies_night_in_l|title=Paralympics: Ladies night in London |date=7 September 2012|accessdate=9 August 2013|publisher=athletics.com.au}}</ref>\n\nKober defended her World titles when she travelled to Lyon for the [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships|2013 World Championships]]. She took both the javelin throw (F33/34) and shot put titles, equaling her world record throw in the javelin.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IPC athlete|id=birgit-kober|old_id=866545}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.birgitkober.de/}} {{in lang|de}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kober, Birgit}}\n[[Category:Paralympic gold medalists for Germany]]\n[[Category:Paralympic athletes of Germany]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:German female javelin throwers]]\n[[Category:German female shot putters]]\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:World record holders in Paralympic athletics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|German Paralympic athlete}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name = Birgit Kober\n| image =2013-04 Birgit Kober.jpg\n| imagesize = <!-- Only for images narrower than 220 pixels -->\n| caption = Kober in April 2013.\n| nationality =[[Germany|German]]\n| sport = [[Track and Field]]\n| event  = [[shot put]]<br/>[[Javelin throw]]\n| club = TSV Bayer 04 Leverkusen\n| collegeteam = \n| coach = Joachim Lipske\n| birth_date ={{Birth date and age|1971|07|10|df=y}}\n| disability= [[Ataxia]]\n| birth_place = [[Munich]], [[West Germany]]\n| residence = \n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| height = \n| weight = \n|website = [https://www.birgitkober.de/ www.birgitkober.de]\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalSport | Women's [[Athletics (sport)|athletics]]}}\n{{MedalCountry |{{GER}} }}\n{{MedalCount\n|[[Summer Paralympic Games|Paralympic Games]]|3|0|0\n|[[IPC Athletics World Championships|World Championships]]|4|0|0\n|[[IPC Athletics European Championships|European Championships]]|5|0|0\n}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[File:IPC logo (2004).svg|25px]] [[Paralympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2012 Summer Paralympics|2012 London]] | [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's shot put|Shot put F33/34]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2012 Summer Paralympics|2012 London]]|[[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's javelin throw|Javelin - F33/34/52/53]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2016 Summer Paralympics|2016 Rio de Janeiro]]|[[Athletics at the 2016 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Women's shot put|Shot put - F36]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[File:IPC logo (2004).svg|25px]] [[IPC Athletics World Championships|IPC World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold|{{nowrap|[[2011 Athletics World Championships|2011 Christchurch]]}}|[[2011 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's shot put|Shot put - F33/34]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2011 Athletics World Championships|2011 Christchurch]]|[[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's javelin throw|Javelin F33/34/52/53]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships|2013 Lyon]] |[[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's shot put|Shot put - F32/33/34]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships|2013 Lyon]] |[[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's javelin throw|Javelin F33/34]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[File:IPC logo (2004).svg|25px]] [[IPC Athletics European Championships|IPC European Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2012 IPC Athletics European Championships|2012 Stadskanaal]]|[[2012 IPC Athletics European Championships \u2013 Women's shot put|Shot put - F34]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2012 IPC Athletics European Championships|2012 Stadskanaal]]|[[2012 IPC Athletics European Championships \u2013 Women's javelin throw|Javelin F33/34/52/53]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2014 IPC Athletics European Championships|2014 Swansea]]|[[2014 IPC Athletics European Championships \u2013 Women's javelin throw|Javelin F34]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2014 IPC Athletics European Championships|2014 Swansea]]|[[2014 IPC Athletics European Championships \u2013 Women's shot put|shot put F34]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2016 IPC Athletics European Championships|2016 Grosseto]]|[[2016 IPC Athletics European Championships \u2013 Women's shot put|shot put F35/36]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Birgit Kober''' (born 10 July 1971) is a German Paralympic athlete.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ipc.infostradasports.com/asp/lib/TheASP.asp?pageid=8937&sportid=-1&personid=866545|title=Kober, Birgit|publisher=IPC Athletics|accessdate=9 August 2013}}</ref> She initially competed in [[T34 (classification)|F34]] seated throwing events, and from 2011-2013 she became the reigning champion at European, World and Paralympic level in both shot put and javelin in her class. At the [[2012 Summer Paralympic Games]] in London, she broke the world record in both her events. Following changes to the [[International Paralympic Committee|IPC]] rules for seated throws in 2014, she chose to compete in a standing position as an [[T36 (classification)|F36]] athlete.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kugelsto\u00dfen mit Birgit Kober \"Nimm die H\u00fcfte mit\"|url=http://www.spiegel.de/gesundheit/ernaehrung/paralympics-kugelstossen-mit-birgit-kober-a-1110340.html|publisher=Der Spiegel|date=16 September 2016|language=German}}</ref> She won the F36 shot put at the [[2016 Summer Paralympic Games]] with a Paralympic record throw. {{As of|April 2017}} she is World Record holder in the Women's F36 shot put, a distance of 11.52 m set in July 2016.<ref>[https://db.ipc-services.org/sdms/web/record/at/pdf/type/WR/category/out/gender/W/evt/SHO  Para Athletics World Records - Women's Shot Put]</ref><ref>[http://www.parasport-news.com/looking-towards-athletics-in-rio-t36-womens-world-records/11001/ Looking towards athletics in Rio: T36 women\u2019s world records]</ref>\n\n==Career history==\n===Early history===\nKober was born in 1971 and grew up in [[Munich]]. She took to sport at a young age, and by 14 she was involved in athletics and the javelin throw while at school in Munich. At the age of 16 a reaction with medical treatment left her deaf, and a year later she suffered an [[epileptic]] seizure. While still a teenager she moved to the Ruhr region where she attended a school for the deaf. She continued her education, specializing in medicine but was forced to cut her studies in 2006 to help care for her sick mother. In 2007 Kober suffered from a [[status epilepticus]] and she was rushed to hospital, but after complications she was left with [[ataxia]].\n\n===Athletics career===\nKober returned to athletics in 2008, mainly as a form of enjoyment with no serious ambitions to take the sport further. She joined [[TSV Bayer 04 Leverkusen]] where she was coached by Joachim Lipske. Kober was quickly identified as a potential talent in throwing events and by 2009 she was competing in national competitions. Classified as a T/F34 category para-athlete, Kober specialized in both the javelin and shot put. She qualified for the [[2011 IPC Athletics World Championships]] in Christchurch, New Zealand, and took gold in both her events. In the shot put, where she competed in a mixed F32/33/34 grouping, she threw a distance of 9.30m, a new world record.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://germanz.co.nz/archiv/ipc-international-paralympic-committee-wm-2011-in-christchurch-neuseeland-2-tag/|title=IPC (International Paralympic Committee) World Cup 2011 in Christchurch, New Zealand - 2  Day|language=German|date=24 January 2011|accessdate=9 August 2013|publisher=germanz.co.nz|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130208185819/http://germanz.co.nz/archiv/ipc-international-paralympic-committee-wm-2011-in-christchurch-neuseeland-2-tag/|archivedate=8 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, in the build-up to the [[2012 Summer Paralympics|Summer Paralympics in London]], she entered the [[2012 IPC Athletics European Championships|European Championships]] in [[Stadskanaal]] in the Netherlands. She again dominated the field taking both gold medals and recording a world record in the shot put with a throw of 10.06m.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ipcat.msl.es/ZBB101A_AT@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@ENG_number=7600.htm|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130809092650/http://ipcat.msl.es/ZBB101A_AT@@@@@@@@@@@@@@@ENG_number=7600.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=9 August 2013|title=Kober, Birgit|accessdate=9 August 2013|publisher=ipcat.msl.es}}</ref> At the Paralympics she recorded a distance of 27.03m in the javelin and three days later she threw 10.25m in the shot put. Both distances were new world records in the F34 classification and gave her gold in both events.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southafrica.info/news/sport/paralympics-040912.htm#.UgSv10VwbIU|title=SA improves on Paralympics medal tally|date=4 September 2012|first=Brad|last=Morgan|accessdate=9 August 2013|publisher=southafrica.info|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140114153810/http://www.southafrica.info/news/sport/paralympics-040912.htm#.UgSv10VwbIU|archive-date=14 January 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.athletics.com.au/home/news/news/2012/september/paralympics_ladies_night_in_l|title=Paralympics: Ladies night in London |date=7 September 2012|accessdate=9 August 2013|publisher=athletics.com.au}}</ref>\n\nKober defended her World titles when she travelled to Lyon for the [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships|2013 World Championships]]. She took both the javelin throw (F33/34) and shot put titles, equaling her world record throw in the javelin.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IPC athlete|866545}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kober, Birgit}}\n[[Category:Paralympic gold medalists for Germany]]\n[[Category:Paralympic athletes of Germany]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:German female javelin throwers]]\n[[Category:German female shot putters]]\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:World record holders in Paralympic athletics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "update IPC external link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Birgit_Kober"}
{"title_page": "Cristina (singer)", "text_new": "{{short description|American singer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name                = Cristina\n| image               = \n| caption             = \n| image_size          = \n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = Cristina Monet-Palaci\n| alias               = Cristina Monet Zilkha\n| birth_place         = \n| birth_date          = {{birth date|1959|1|2}}\n| death_date          =  {{death date and age|2020|4|1|1959|1|2}}\n| origin              = [[New York City]], U.S.\n| instrument          = \n| genre               = [[No wave]], [[synthpop]]\n| occupation          = Singer\n| years_active        = 1978\u20131984\n| label               = [[ZE Records|ZE]], [[Mercury Records|Mercury]]\n| associated_acts     = \n| website             = \n}}\n\n'''Cristina Monet Zilkha''' ({{nee}} '''Monet-Palaci''',<ref name=engaged/> January 2, 1959 \u2013 April 1, 2020),<ref name=\"wheeler1\">{{cite news |last1=Wheeler |first1=Andr\u00e9 |title=Things Fall Apart singer Cristina reportedly dies from coronavirus |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/apr/01/pop-singer-cristina-coronavirus-us |accessdate=2 April 2020 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=April 1, 2020}}</ref> known during her recording career [[mononymously]] as '''Cristina''', was an American singer and writer, best known for her [[new wave]] recordings made for [[ZE Records]] in the late 1970s and early 1980s in [[New York City]].\n\n==Biography==\nA [[Harvard]] dropout,<ref name=\"rocks\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.redoverwhite.org/cristina/rocks_cristina.html|title=Cristina * Boston Globe article (1980)|website=Redoverwhite.org}}</ref> and the daughter of a French psychoanalyst and an American illustrator-novelist-playwright, she was working as a writer for ''[[The Village Voice]]'' when she met [[Michael Zilkha]], who later became her husband.<ref name=\"queen\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.redoverwhite.org/cristina/queen_cristina.html|title=Cristina * Time Out New York article (2004)|website=Redoverwhite.org}}</ref><ref name=engaged>{{cite news|title=Cristina Monet-Palaci And Michael Zilkha Engaged |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/12/12/style/cristina-monet-palaci-and-michael-zilkha-engaged.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]]| accessdate=28 June 2018 |date=December 12, 1982}}</ref> A wealthy heir to England's Mothercare retail empire, Michael started ZE Records with [[Michel Esteban]]. Zilkha persuaded her to record a song titled \"Disco Clone\", an eccentric pastiche dance record written by Ronald Melrose, a classmate of hers at Harvard.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.zerecords.com/2010/about_interview_1.php|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100916210655/http://www.zerecords.com/2010/about_interview_1.php|url-status=dead|title=''Strange Days'' magazine: 2009 interview with Michel Esteban|archivedate=September 16, 2010}}</ref> The original recording, released as ZE001 in 1978, was produced by [[John Cale]] and was the first to be issued on the ZE label.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://lineout.thestranger.com/2007/03/cristina_disco_clone_prod_by_john_cale |title=Cristina \u2013 Disco Clone Prod. By John Cale {{!}} Line Out {{!}} The Stranger's Music Blog |access-date=July 28, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717033928/http://lineout.thestranger.com/2007/03/cristina_disco_clone_prod_by_john_cale |archive-date=July 17, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> A later version featured the uncredited [[Kevin Kline]] trying to seduce Cristina,<ref name=\"queen\" /> replacing [[Anthony Haden-Guest]] on the original record.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=POIVBgAAQBAJ&pg=PT167&lpg=PT167&dq=%22Disco+Clone%22+Haden+Guest&source=bl&ots=LOzWqcJ1ph&sig=ACfU3U3p9xgB4JOfQg5L6IDz1oOc5BHsMw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiFhePams_mAhVjolwKHQVRCTIQ6AEwBXoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22Disco+Clone%22+Haden+Guest&f=false|title=The Last Party: Studio 54, Disco, and the Culture of the Night|first=Anthony|last=Haden-Guest|date=February 17, 2015|publisher=Open Road Media|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n\"Disco Clone\" was a cult success and encouraged ZE to release a full-length album in 1980, which was produced by [[August Darnell]] of [[Kid Creole & The Coconuts]].<ref name=\"queen\" /> The album was reissued as ''Doll in the Box''. Cristina also issued on a 12\" single a cover of [[Peggy Lee]]'s \"[[Is That All There Is?]]\" with new, satirical lyrics. Its authors [[Leiber and Stoller]] sued and successfully got it withdrawn for many years.<ref name=\"rocks\" /> Later, she released a cover of [[the Beatles]]' \"[[Drive My Car]]\" (also released as \"Baby You Can Drive My Car\"). She released the track \"Things Fall Apart\", produced by [[Was (Not Was)]], on ZE's ''[[A Christmas Record|Christmas Record]]'', in 1981.\n\nCristina's second album ''Sleep It Off'' was produced by [[Don Was]] and released in 1984 with a sleeve design by [[Jean-Paul Goude]] (a year before he used the same idea for [[Grace Jones]]). The lyrics satirized urban decadence with often dry, sarcastic delivery. The record flopped, and Cristina retired to domestic life in [[Texas]]. The album was re-released in 2004 with six bonus tracks, two of which were produced (and one co-written) by [[Robert Palmer (singer)|Robert Palmer]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Cristina \u2014 Sleep It Off |url=https://www.discogs.com/Cristina-Sleep-It-Off/release/554612 |website=Discogs.com |accessdate=28 June 2018}}</ref> &nbsp;\n\nMonet-Palaci and Zilkha divorced in 1990, and she returned to New York City.<ref name=\"queen\" /> She later contributed learned essays and reviews to publications such as London's ''[[Times Literary Supplement]]'' while battling a debilitating illness.<ref name=\"queen\" /> Her two albums for ZE were reissued in 2004.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dustedmagazine.com/reviews/1934|title=Dusted Reviews \u2013 Cristina|website=Dustedmagazine.com}}</ref>\n\nCristina died on April 1, 2020, at the age of 61, reportedly from [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]].<ref name=wheeler1 />\n\n==Discography==\n{{Infobox artist discography\n| Artist       = Cristina\n| Image        = \n| Caption      = \n| Studio       = 2\n| Live         = \n| Compilation  = \n| Video        = \n| Music videos = \n| Tribute      = \n| EP           = \n| Singles      = 6\n| Singles link = \n| B-sides      = \n| Soundtrack   = \n| References   = \n}}\n\n===Studio albums===\n* ''Cristina''  (1980, ZE Records)\n* ''[[Sleep It Off]]'' (1984, [[Mercury Records]])\n* ''Doll in the Box'' (2004, ZE Records) \u2013 Expanded re-issue of ''Cristina''\n* ''Sleep It Off'' (2004, ZE Records) \u2013 Expanded re-issue\n\n===Singles===\n* \"Disco Clone\" (1978)\n* \"[[Is That All There Is?]]\" (1980)\n* \"[[Drive My Car]]\" (also released as \"Baby You Can Drive My Car\") (1980)<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.discogs.com/Cristina-Drive-My-Car/master/196274 |title=Cristina \u2013 Drive My Car |website=[[Discogs.com]] |accessdate=2014-07-25}}</ref>\n* \"[[La Poup\u00e9e qui fait non]]\" (1980)\n* \"Things Fall Apart\" (1981)\n* \"Ticket to the Tropics\" (1984)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.redoverwhite.org/cristina/ Fan site]\n* [http://zerecords.com/artist/12/cristina.html Discography on ZE Records]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140202185748/http://www2.odn.ne.jp/airstructures/review%20newwave%20diva.html#cristina Vinyl discography] at the [[Wayback Machine]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110929034859/http://www.richardstrange.com/writing/writeb8.htm Essay] by [[Richard Strange]] at the Wayback Machine\n\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cristina}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:No wave musicians]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing]]\n[[Category:ZE Records artists]]\n[[Category:American people of French descent]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American singer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name                = Cristina\n| image               = \n| caption             = \n| image_size          = \n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = Cristina Monet-Palaci\n| alias               = Cristina Monet Zilkha\n| birth_place         = \n| birth_date          = {{birth date|1959|1|2}}\n| death_date          =  {{death date and age|2020|4|1|1959|1|2}}\n| origin              = [[New York City]], U.S.\n| instrument          = \n| genre               = [[No wave]], [[synthpop]]\n| occupation          = Singer\n| years_active        = 1978\u20131984\n| label               = [[ZE Records|ZE]], [[Mercury Records|Mercury]]\n| associated_acts     = \n| website             = \n}}\n\n'''Cristina Monet Zilkha''' ({{nee}} '''Monet-Palaci''',<ref name=engaged/> January 2, 1959 \u2013 April 1, 2020),<ref name=\"wheeler1\">{{cite news |last1=Wheeler |first1=Andr\u00e9 |title=Things Fall Apart singer Cristina reportedly dies from coronavirus |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/apr/01/pop-singer-cristina-coronavirus-us |accessdate=2 April 2020 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=April 1, 2020}}</ref> known during her recording career [[mononymously]] as '''Cristina''', was an American singer and writer, best known for her [[new wave]] recordings made for [[ZE Records]] in the late 1970s and early 1980s in [[New York City]].\n\n==Biography==\nA [[Harvard]] dropout,<ref name=\"rocks\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.redoverwhite.org/cristina/rocks_cristina.html|title=Cristina * Boston Globe article (1980)|website=Redoverwhite.org}}</ref> and the daughter of a French psychoanalyst and an American illustrator-novelist-playwright, she was working as a writer for ''[[The Village Voice]]'' when she met [[Michael Zilkha]], who later became her husband.<ref name=\"queen\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.redoverwhite.org/cristina/queen_cristina.html|title=Cristina * Time Out New York article (2004)|website=Redoverwhite.org}}</ref><ref name=engaged>{{cite news|title=Cristina Monet-Palaci And Michael Zilkha Engaged |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/12/12/style/cristina-monet-palaci-and-michael-zilkha-engaged.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]]| accessdate=28 June 2018 |date=December 12, 1982}}</ref> A wealthy heir to England's Mothercare retail empire, Michael started ZE Records with [[Michel Esteban]]. Zilkha persuaded her to record a song titled \"Disco Clone\", an eccentric pastiche dance record written by Ronald Melrose, a classmate of hers at Harvard.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.zerecords.com/2010/about_interview_1.php|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100916210655/http://www.zerecords.com/2010/about_interview_1.php|url-status=dead|title=''Strange Days'' magazine: 2009 interview with Michel Esteban|archivedate=September 16, 2010}}</ref> The original recording, released as ZE001 in 1978, was produced by [[John Cale]] and was the first to be issued on the ZE label.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://lineout.thestranger.com/2007/03/cristina_disco_clone_prod_by_john_cale |title=Cristina \u2013 Disco Clone Prod. By John Cale {{!}} Line Out {{!}} The Stranger's Music Blog |access-date=July 28, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717033928/http://lineout.thestranger.com/2007/03/cristina_disco_clone_prod_by_john_cale |archive-date=July 17, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> A later version featured the uncredited [[Kevin Kline]] trying to seduce Cristina,<ref name=\"queen\" /> replacing [[Anthony Haden-Guest]] on the original record. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=POIVBgAAQBAJ&pg=PT167&lpg=PT167&dq=%22Disco+Clone%22+Haden+Guest&source=bl&ots=LOzWqcJ1ph&sig=ACfU3U3p9xgB4JOfQg5L6IDz1oOc5BHsMw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiFhePams_mAhVjolwKHQVRCTIQ6AEwBXoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22Disco+Clone%22+Haden+Guest&f=false|title=The Last Party: Studio 54, Disco, and the Culture of the Night|first=Anthony|last=Haden-Guest|date=February 17, 2015|publisher=Open Road Media|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n\"Disco Clone\" was a cult success and encouraged ZE to release a full-length album in 1980, which was produced by [[August Darnell]] of [[Kid Creole & The Coconuts]].<ref name=\"queen\" /> The album was reissued as ''Doll in the Box''. Cristina also issued on a 12\" single a cover of [[Peggy Lee]]'s \"[[Is That All There Is?]]\" with new, satirical lyrics. Its authors [[Leiber and Stoller]] sued and successfully got it withdrawn for many years.<ref name=\"rocks\" /> Later, she released a cover of [[the Beatles]]' \"[[Drive My Car]]\" (also released as \"Baby You Can Drive My Car\"). She released the track \"Things Fall Apart\", produced by [[Was (Not Was)]], on ZE's ''[[A Christmas Record|Christmas Record]]'', in 1981.\n\nCristina's second album ''Sleep It Off'' was produced by [[Don Was]] and released in 1984 with a sleeve design by [[Jean-Paul Goude]] (a year before he used the same idea for [[Grace Jones]]). The lyrics satirized urban decadence with often dry, sarcastic delivery. The record flopped, and Cristina retired to domestic life in [[Texas]]. The album was re-released in 2004 with six bonus tracks, two of which were produced (and one co-written) by [[Robert Palmer (singer)|Robert Palmer]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Cristina \u2014 Sleep It Off |url=https://www.discogs.com/Cristina-Sleep-It-Off/release/554612 |website=Discogs.com |accessdate=28 June 2018}}</ref> &nbsp;\n\nMonet-Palaci and Zilkha divorced in 1990, and she returned to New York City.<ref name=\"queen\" /> She later contributed learned essays and reviews to publications such as London's ''[[Times Literary Supplement]]'' while battling a debilitating illness.<ref name=\"queen\" /> Her two albums for ZE were reissued in 2004.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dustedmagazine.com/reviews/1934|title=Dusted Reviews \u2013 Cristina|website=Dustedmagazine.com}}</ref>\n\nCristina died on April 1, 2020, at the age of 61, reportedly from [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]].<ref name=wheeler1 />\n\n==Discography==\n{{Infobox artist discography\n| Artist       = Cristina\n| Image        = \n| Caption      = \n| Studio       = 2\n| Live         = \n| Compilation  = \n| Video        = \n| Music videos = \n| Tribute      = \n| EP           = \n| Singles      = 6\n| Singles link = \n| B-sides      = \n| Soundtrack   = \n| References   = \n}}\n\n===Studio albums===\n* ''Cristina''  (1980, ZE Records)\n* ''[[Sleep It Off]]'' (1984, [[Mercury Records]])\n* ''Doll in the Box'' (2004, ZE Records) \u2013 Expanded re-issue of ''Cristina''\n* ''Sleep It Off'' (2004, ZE Records) \u2013 Expanded re-issue\n\n===Singles===\n* \"Disco Clone\" (1978)\n* \"[[Is That All There Is?]]\" (1980)\n* \"[[Drive My Car]]\" (also released as \"Baby You Can Drive My Car\") (1980)<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.discogs.com/Cristina-Drive-My-Car/master/196274 |title=Cristina \u2013 Drive My Car |website=[[Discogs.com]] |accessdate=2014-07-25}}</ref>\n* \"[[La Poup\u00e9e qui fait non]]\" (1980)\n* \"Things Fall Apart\" (1981)\n* \"Ticket to the Tropics\" (1984)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.redoverwhite.org/cristina/ Fan site]\n* [http://zerecords.com/artist/12/cristina.html Discography on ZE Records]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140202185748/http://www2.odn.ne.jp/airstructures/review%20newwave%20diva.html#cristina Vinyl discography] at the [[Wayback Machine]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110929034859/http://www.richardstrange.com/writing/writeb8.htm Essay] by [[Richard Strange]] at the Wayback Machine\n\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEF